%S A392984 -1,1,-1,1,-1,3,-5,-3,-1,3,-7,1,-3,-5,3,-3,-1,3,-3,-9,-1,-1,1,1,-11,1,
%T A392984 -7,-5,-3,5,7,-1,3,-15,3,-5,3,-11,-3,5,9,5,5,1,-5,-3,-19,-7,-13,-7,-5,
%U A392984 1,15,13,-7,-9,-15,1,1,-5,-5,13,3,-15,-11,-1,9,-1,-9,7,-5,5,9,-5,7,-5,-3,13,-17,-9
%N A392984 a(n) = (A_0 - A_2)/p where p is the n-th prime == 5 (mod 8) with p >= 13, A_0 is the sum of quartic residues mod p, and A_2 is the sum of quadratic-non-quartic residues mod p.
%C A392984 For a prime p == 1 (mod 4), the multiplicative group (Z/pZ)* partitions into four cosets of the quartic residue subgroup. Coset 0 consists of the quartic residues {n : n^((p-1)/4) == 1 (mod p)} and Coset 2 consists of the quadratic-non-quartic residues {n : n^((p-1)/4) == -1 (mod p)}. The k-invariant k(p) = (A_0 - A_2)/p, where A_j = sum of elements in Coset j.
%C A392984 The definition is canonical: the assignment of elements to Cosets 0 and 2 is independent of the choice of primitive root. Only Cosets 1 and 3 are swapped under the ambiguity chi_4 <-> conjugate(chi_4).
%C A392984 For primes p == 1 (mod 8), the quartic character chi_4 is even, so L(chi_4, 0) = 0 by the vanishing of B_{1,chi} for even characters. This means A_0 - A_2 = 0 for all such primes, so the k-invariant is trivially zero. The sequence is therefore restricted to primes p == 5 (mod 8), where the quartic character is odd and k(p) is a nonzero odd integer.
%C A392984 By the classical identity L(chi,0) = -B_{1,chi} (Leopoldt, 1958), combined with the Carlitz-Barsky integrality theorem, k(p) = -Re(L(chi_4, 0)) where chi_4 is the quartic Dirichlet character mod p. Since chi_4 is odd for p == 5 (mod 8), L(chi_4, 0) is a Gaussian integer, so k(p) is an integer.
%C A392984 a(n) is always an odd integer for n >= 2. This follows from the (1+i)-adic valuation of L(chi_4, 0) being exactly 1 for primes p == 5 (mod 8), p >= 13.
%C A392984 The prime p = 5 (= A007521(1)) is excluded because k(5) = -3/5 is not an integer (the unique exception in this congruence class).
%C A392984 |k(p)| << sqrt(p) * log(p) by the Polya-Vinogradov inequality. In practice |k(p)| is much smaller: the largest |k| observed for p < 10^6 is 71.
%C A392984 The companion sequence t(p) = (A_1 - A_3)/p (using Cosets 1 and 3) is also always an odd integer for these primes. Together, k(p) + i*t(p) = -L(chi_4, 0) is a Gaussian integer.
%H A392984 Joseph Farland, <a href="/A392984/b392984.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..569</a>
%F A392984 a(n) = (A_0 - A_2)/p where p = A007521(n), A_0 = Sum_{m=1..p-1, m^((p-1)/4) == 1 (mod p)} m, A_2 = Sum_{m=1..p-1, m^((p-1)/4) == p-1 (mod p)} m.
%F A392984 Equivalently, a(n) = -Re(L(chi_4, 0)) where chi_4 is a quartic Dirichlet character mod p. Since L(chi_4, 0) = -B_{1,chi_4} by the Leopoldt formula, and B_{1,chi_4} = (1/p) * Sum_{m=1..p-1} chi_4(m)*m, this gives a(n) = -Re(B_{1,chi_4}).
%e A392984 For p = 13 (the first prime == 5 (mod 8) with p >= 13):
%e A392984   Quartic residues (Coset 0): {1, 3, 9} since 1^3=1, 3^3=27==1, 9^3=729==1 (mod 13).
%e A392984   Quadratic-non-quartic (Coset 2): {4, 10, 12} since 4^3=64==12==-1, 10^3=1000==12==-1, 12^3=1728==12==-1 (mod 13).
%e A392984   A_0 = 1 + 3 + 9 = 13; A_2 = 4 + 10 + 12 = 26.
%e A392984   k(13) = (13 - 26)/13 = -1, so a(1) = -1.
%e A392984 For p = 29: A_0 = 116, A_2 = 87, k(29) = (116-87)/29 = 1, so a(2) = 1.
%e A392984 For p = 101: A_0 = 1414, A_2 = 1111, k(101) = 303/101 = 3, so a(6) = 3.
%e A392984 For p = 109: A_0 = 1199, A_2 = 1744, k(109) = -545/109 = -5, so a(7) = -5.
%t A392984 kInvariant[p_] := Module[{e = (p-1)/4, A0 = 0, A2 = 0}, Do[Which[PowerMod[n, e, p] == 1, A0 += n, PowerMod[n, e, p] == p-1, A2 += n], {n, 1, p-1}]; (A0 - A2)/p];
%t A392984 Select[Prime[Range[400]], Mod[#, 8] == 5 && # >= 13 &] // Map[kInvariant]
%o A392984 (Python)
%o A392984 from sympy import primerange
%o A392984 def k_inv(p):
%o A392984     e = (p - 1) // 4
%o A392984     A0 = sum(n for n in range(1, p) if pow(n, e, p) == 1)
%o A392984     A2 = sum(n for n in range(1, p) if pow(n, e, p) == p - 1)
%o A392984     return (A0 - A2) // p
%o A392984 print([k_inv(p) for p in primerange(13, 3000) if p % 8 == 5])
